  • Psammoma bodies (Form of dystrophic calcification) are present on histology.
    -

#2015MCQ-OCT/Q42
They occur due to defects in haem synthesis.

  • Defects early in the pathway produce precursors which are neurotoxic and produce acute porphyrias. They show #autosomalDominant inheritance.
    • It causes a photosensitive blistering rash.

Mnemonic: AIP will be 'invisible' - no visible skin changes.

  • Clinical features: *Abdominal pain, neuropsychiatric features, seizures and fever and peripheral neuropathies.
    • Depression is common. (also schizophrenia)
    • Peripheral neuropathies mimicking Guillain Barre syndrome. (can have areflexia)
      • Autonomic disturbances.
    • Skin manifestations ARE NOT A FEATURE OF AIP
  • Can be precipitated by anaesthetic drugs and luteal phase of the menstrual cycle.
  • The defective enzyme in acute intermittent porphyria is porphobilinogen deaminase.
  • Diagnosis: urinary porphobilinogen - negative test excludes porphyria.
  • 80% of cases are acquired / sporadic; 20% are inherited. (? #x-linked-Dominant forms may occur) [[2020-BasicSciences-July#List of X linked dominant diseases]]
  • Presents with photosensitive blistering rash.
  • Hypertrichosis and hyperpigmentation may be present.
  • Liver disease is a common comorbidity:
    • liver disease due to hepatitis C / alcohol triggering porphyria.
  • Triggers for attacks are caused by increased hepatic iron load but also alcohol, smoking, estrogens, hepatitis C or HIV.
  • Phlebotomy - used to decrease the iron load
  • Hydroxycholorquine - increase the excretion of porphyrins.
  1. [[#Spinocerebellar ataxia (SCA)]]

Spinocerebellar ataxia (SCA)

#autosomalDominant

  • Neurodenerative disease which affects the cerebellum.
  • main cell involved in degeneration is the Purkinje cells.
  • A "slowly progressive cerebellar syndrome" with oculomotor, retinal, pyramidal (spacticity) , extrapyramidal, sensory, and cognitive/behavioral symptoms that vary with the affected gene.
    • Gait ataxia
    • Nystagmus
    • Dys
  • Most are adult onset.

In adults, the cord terminates at the level of L1-L2. Thus the cord spans within 20 bony vertebrae. In a child, it terminates at the upper border of L3.

  • Increased preload AND increased afterload will (counterintuitively) decrease the MVP murmur.

The most common presenting symptom is dyspnea followed by chest pain (classically pleuritic in nature, but not always), cough, and symptoms of deep venous thrombosis.
Hemoptysis is an unusual presenting symptom.
With severe PE, patients can present with shock, arrhythmia, or syncope. Many patients are asymptomatic; high index of suspicion is needed.
Cyanosis is not a feature of pumonary embolism; presence suggests a massive PE. Source

ECG Features:

  • Rate - Sinus tachy
  • RBBB
  • Right ventricular strain pattern (T in V1-V4 and inferior leads)
  • R wave - Dominant R way in V one
  • Rotation - clock wise rotation - Shift of R/S transition point towards V6
  • Right atrial enlargement
  • SI,QIII,TIII pattern - non specific and non sensitive.

Diagnosis

Suspect based on wells score.
CT-PA -> if N/A -> V/Q scan -> NA -> USS of Deep veins.

  • Mainstay is anticoagulation.
  • Thrombolysis / embolectomy / ?IVC filter is reserved for PE with life threatening hypotension.

Liver failure -> LMWH (liver LMWH)
Kidney failure -> VKA (Kidney VKA)
Pregnancy = Mother -> LMWH (Mom LMWH)

  • Commonest early complication is recurrence; risk is reduced by anticoagulation.
  • Commonest late complication is CTEPH. (chronic thromboembolic pulmonary hypertension)
  • Bleeding from anticoagulation.

#autosomalDominant

  • There is bilateral ptosis.
  • Wasting of the temporalis and masseter muscles contributes to a thin visage referred to as a hatchet face. Sternomastoid atrophy causes a pencil necked appearance. Source
  • Muscles are slow to relax. (myotonia) [[#Myotonia]]
    • Eg: Difficulty releasing grip on a doorknob.

Other systems are widely affected:

  • "often affects the electrical conduction system of the heart, breathing and swallowing muscles, bowels, lens of the eye (cataracts) and brain"
  • Other features:
    • Cataracts
    • Ptosis
    • Early balding
    • Subfertility
    • Diabetes
      Myotonic dystrophy can show genetic anticipation.
      Myotonia congenita:
  • Sweet tasting. (animal poisoning is common from radiator leaks)
  • Like ethyl alcohol and methanol, ethylene glycol is metabolized by ADH. (alcohol dehydrogenase) In this step it forms glycoaldehyde. Through interaction with aldehyde dehydrogenase, ethylene glycol is then metabolized to glycolic acid (GA), which accumulates and can cause a profound metabolic acidosis. This glycolic acid is eventually converted into glyoxylic acid, and then into the highly toxic oxalate or the safer glutamate or -ketoadipic acid metabolites.
  • Ethylene glycol -> glycoaldehyde -> glycolid acid ( ph) -> glycoxylic acid -> oxalate.
  • Toxic dose: 200ml of 50% solution.
    - Mnemonic: CNS depression in hours -> Kidney on organ injury in next 1 to 2 days.
    - 30 mins to 12 hours : Ethanol like effects on the CNS.
    - 12 to 48 hours: metabolite (glycolic acid) produces severe high anion gap metabolic acidosis. Calcium oxalate crystals become deposited in brain, lungs kidneys and heart.
    - 24 to 72 hours, acute kidney injury can result from the direct renal toxic effects of the ethylene glycol metabolite calcium oxalate monohydrate.
  • Diagnosis
    • Causes an increased oslmolar gap. (osmoles which are unaccounted for by Sodium , glucose and urea)
    • Plasma osmolality: Posm =2 [Na(+)]+glucose (mg/dL)/18+BUN (mg/dL)//2.8
    • Causes of increased osmolar gap : Alcohol (ethanol, methanol, ethylene glycol poisoning)
    • Initial emergency department treatment includes infusion of crystalloids to enhance renal clearance of the toxic metabolites.
    • Ethyl alcohol (ethanol) has traditionally been used for antidotal treatment, but it has largely been supplanted by fomepizole in the United States.

Fatty cast:

Composed of Tamm-Horsfall protein which is made by the renal tubular epithelium.

  • Hyaline casts - only tamm horsfall protein; least significant type of cast.
  • Granular casts - consist of cell debris, plasma proteins (fibrinogen, immune complexes).
    • Course, deeply pigmented, muddy brown casts are considered characteristic of ATN.
    • Pyelonephritis
    • Glomerulonephritis
    • Presence of red cells in the cast => Glomerular injury.
  • Fatty casts / urinary lipids (cholesterol esters) : nephrotic syndrome, mercury poisoning, ethylene glycol poisoning.
  • WBC casts - interstitial nephritis, pyelonephritis.
  • Tubular epithelial cell casts : ATN, acute interstitial nephritis, proliferative glomerulonephritis.
  • Strenuous exercise: Can cause haemauria (i.e red cells in urine) Mechanisms are unknown -> Possibly lactic acid causing increased glomerular permeability or exercise induced renal ischemia.
    • "hepatic" are the commonest extrarenal manifestations - 70%.
  • Cardiovascular:
    • Mitral valve prolapse.
  • NAPQI binds irreversibly to mitochondrial proteins.

"The mechanism by which toxicity results is complex, but is believed to involve reaction between unconjugated NAPQI and critical proteins as well as increased susceptibility to oxidative stress caused by the depletion of glutathione.4"

While NADH is the ultimate electron donor for many redox reactions, including oxidative phosphorylation, glutathione (GSH) is the major ROS detoxifying redox buffer in the cell.
[!INFO] Mechanism of NAC
Although some controversy persists regarding mechanism, most toxicologists believe N-acetylcysteine prevents acetaminophen-induced hepatic injury by restoring hepatic glutathione stores.
